  <span class="word-strongs"><a href="../lexicon/h6083.html">H6083</a></span>
</span><span class="interlinear-word" data-strongs="H9008">
  <span class="word-original hebrew">הֲ/יַגִּ֥יד</span>
  <span class="word-translit">ha/yaGid</span>
  <span class="word-english">¿/ will it declare</span>
  <span class="word-strongs">H9008</span>
</span><span class="interlinear-word" data-strongs="H571">
  <span class="word-original hebrew">אֲמִתֶּֽ/ךָ\׃</span>
  <span class="word-translit">&#x27;amiTe/kha</span>
  <span class="word-english">faithfulness/ your</span>
  <span class="word-strongs"><a href="../lexicon/h571.html">H571</a></span>
</span></div>
    <div class="tn-note">
      <strong>&#x1f4dd; Cultural Note:</strong> David is using a question to emphasize that his death would not benefit God and to make the point that dead people cannot praise God. If a speaker of your language would not use the question form for this purpose, you could translate these questions as statements or exclamations. Alternate translation: [There is no profit in my blood, in my descent to the pit. The dust will not praise you! It will
    </div>
    <div class="tn-note">
      <strong>&#x1f4dd; Cultural Note:</strong> These two phrases mean basically the same thing. The second emphasizes the meaning of the first by repeating the same idea with different words. Hebrew poetry was based on this kind of repetition, and you may want to show this to your readers by including both phrases in your translation. If it is helpful, you could connect the phrases in a way that shows that the second phrase is repeating the fi
    </div>
    <div class="tn-note">
      <strong>&#x1f4dd; Cultural Note:</strong> Here, **blood** represents “death.” If it would be helpful in your language, you could use an equivalent expression or plain language. Alternate translation: [in my death]
    </div><div class="interlinear-verse hebrew-verse"><span class="verse-num">10</span><span class="interlinear-word" data-strongs="H8085">
  <span class="word-original hebrew">שְׁמַע\־</span>
  <span class="word-translit">shema&#x27;-</span>
  <span class="word-english">hear</span>
  <span class="word-strongs"><a href="../lexicon/h8085.html">H8085</a></span>
</span><span class="interlinear-word" data-strongs="H3068">
  <span class="word-original hebrew">יְהוָ֥ה</span>
  <span class="word-translit">Yahweh</span>
  <span class="word-english">O Yahweh</span>
  <span class="word-strongs"><a href="../lexicon/h3068.html">H3068</a></span>
</span><span class="interlinear-word" data-strongs="H9002">
  <span class="word-original hebrew">וְ/חָנֵּ֑/נִי</span>
  <span class="word-translit">ve/choNe/ni</span>
  <span class="word-english">and/ show favor to/ me</span>
  <span class="word-strongs">H9002</span>
</span><span class="interlinear-word" data-strongs="H3068">
  <span class="word-original hebrew">יְ֝הוָה</span>
  <span class="word-translit">Yahweh</span>
  <span class="word-english">O Yahweh</span>
  <span class="word-strongs"><a href="../lexicon/h3068.html">H3068</a></span>
</span><span class="interlinear-word" data-strongs="H1961">
  <span class="word-original hebrew">הֱֽיֵה\־</span>
  <span class="word-translit">heyeh-</span>
  <span class="word-english">be</span>
  <span class="word-strongs"><a href="../lexicon/h1961.html">H1961</a></span>
</span><span class="interlinear-word" data-strongs="H5826">
  <span class="word-original hebrew">עֹזֵ֥ר</span>
  <span class="word-translit">&#x27;oZer</span>
  <span class="word-english">a helper</span>
  <span class="word-strongs"><a href="../lexicon/h5826.html">H5826</a></span>
</span><span class="interlinear-word" data-strongs="H9005">
  <span class="word-original hebrew">לִֽ/י\׃</span>
  <span class="word-translit">L/i</span>
  <span class="word-english">of/ me</span>
  <span class="word-strongs">H9005</span>
</span></div>
    <div class="tn-note">
      <strong>&#x1f4dd; Cultural Note:</strong> Here, **Hear** represents “Listen and respond.” If it would be helpful in your language, you could use an equivalent expression or plain language. Alternate translation: [Listen to me and respond] or [Pay attention to me]
    </div>
    <div class="tn-note">
      <strong>&#x1f4dd; Cultural Note:</strong> David is using imperative forms, but he is communicating polite requests rather than commands. If the imperative forms **Hear**, **be gracious to me**, and **be my helper** do not communicate polite requests in your language, then use a form in your language that communicates a polite request. It may be helpful to add an expression such as “please” to make this clear. Alternate translation: [Pleas
    </div><div class="interlinear-verse hebrew-verse"><span class="verse-num">11</span><span class="interlinear-word" data-strongs="H2015">
  <span class="word-original hebrew">הָפַ֣כְתָּ</span>
  <span class="word-translit">haFakhta</span>
  <span class="word-english">you turned</span>
  <span class="word-strongs"><a href="../lexicon/h2015.html">H2015</a></span>
</span><span class="interlinear-word" data-strongs="H4553">
  <span class="word-original hebrew">מִסְפְּדִ/י֮</span>
  <span class="word-translit">mispeD/i</span>
  <span class="word-english">wailing/ my</span>
  <span class="word-strongs"><a href="../lexicon/h4553.html">H4553</a></span>
</span><span class="interlinear-word" data-strongs="H9005">
  <span class="word-original hebrew">לְ/מָח֪וֹל</span>
  <span class="word-translit">le/maChol</span>
  <span class="word-english">into/ dancing</span>
  <span class="word-strongs">H9005</span>
</span><span class="interlinear-word" data-strongs="H9005">
  <span class="word-original hebrew">לִ֥/י</span>
  <span class="word-translit">l/i</span>
  <span class="word-english">to/ me</span>
  <span class="word-strongs">H9005</span>
</span><span class="interlinear-word" data-strongs="H6605">
  <span class="word-original hebrew">פִּתַּ֥חְתָּ</span>
  <span class="word-translit">piTachta</span>
  <span class="word-english">you loosened</span>
  <span class="word-strongs"><a href="../lexicon/h6605.html">H6605</a></span>
</span><span class="interlinear-word" data-strongs="H8242">
  <span class="word-original hebrew">שַׂקִּ֑/י</span>
  <span class="word-translit">saK/i</span>
  <span class="word-english">sackcloth/ my</span>
  <span class="word-strongs"><a href="../lexicon/h8242.html">H8242</a></span>
</span><span class="interlinear-word" data-strongs="H9001">
  <span class="word-original hebrew">וַֽ/תְּאַזְּרֵ֥/נִי</span>
  <span class="word-translit">va/te&#x27;azeRe/ni</span>
  <span class="word-english">and/ you girded/ me</span>
  <span class="word-strongs">H9001</span>
</span><span class="interlinear-word" data-strongs="H8057">
  <span class="word-original hebrew">שִׂמְחָֽה\׃</span>
  <span class="word-translit">simChah</span>
  <span class="word-english">joy</span>
  <span class="word-strongs"><a href="../lexicon/h8057.html">H8057</a></span>
</span></div>
    <div class="tn-note">
      <strong>&#x1f4dd; Cultural Note:</strong> David assumes that readers will know **sackcloth** was a coarse material worn as a sign of mourning or distress. You could say that explicitly if that would be helpful to your readers. Alternate translation: [you have removed my mourning clothes and have clothed me with gladness]
    </div>
    <div class="tn-note">
      <strong>&#x1f4dd; Cultural Note:</strong> Here, **gladness** represents clothing that was worn for joyous occasions that would express gladness. If it would be helpful in your language, you could use an equivalent expression or plain language. Alternate translation: [with celebratory clothes] or [with clothes worn to celebrate]
    </div>
    <div class="tn-note">
      <strong>&#x1f4dd; Cultural Note:</strong> If your language does not use an abstract noun for the idea of **gladness**, you could express the same idea in another way. Alternate translation: [and have covered me with clothes that show that I am glad] or [and have clothed me with celebratory clothes]
    </div><div class="interlinear-verse hebrew-verse"><span class="verse-num">12</span><span class="interlinear-word" data-strongs="H4616">
  <span class="word-original hebrew">לְמַ֤עַן\׀</span>
  <span class="word-translit">leMa&#x27;an</span>
  <span class="word-english">so that</span>
  <span class="word-strongs"><a href="../lexicon/h4616.html">H4616</a></span>
</span><span class="interlinear-word" data-strongs="H2167">
  <span class="word-original hebrew">יְזַמֶּרְ/ךָ֣</span>
  <span class="word-translit">yezamer/Kha</span>
  <span class="word-english">it may sing praises to/ you</span>
  <span class="word-strongs"><a href="../lexicon/h2167.html">H2167</a></span>
</span><span class="interlinear-word" data-strongs="H3519">
  <span class="word-original hebrew">כָ֭בוֹד</span>
  <span class="word-translit">KhaVod</span>
  <span class="word-english">honor</span>
  <span class="word-strongs"><a href="../lexicon/h3519.html">H3519</a></span>
</span><span class="interlinear-word" data-strongs="H9002">
  <span class="word-original hebrew">וְ/לֹ֣א</span>
  <span class="word-translit">ve/Lo&#x27;</span>
  <span class="word-english">and/ not</span>
  <span class="word-strongs">H9002</span>
</span><span class="interlinear-word" data-strongs="H1826">
  <span class="word-original hebrew">יִדֹּ֑ם</span>
  <span class="word-translit">yiDom</span>
  <span class="word-english">it may be silent</span>
  <span class="word-strongs"><a href="../lexicon/h1826.html">H1826</a></span>
</span><span class="interlinear-word" data-strongs="H3068">
  <span class="word-original hebrew">יְהוָ֥ה</span>
  <span class="word-translit">Yahweh</span>
  <span class="word-english">O Yahweh</span>
  <span class="word-strongs"><a href="../lexicon/h3068.html">H3068</a></span>
</span><span class="interlinear-word" data-strongs="H430">
  <span class="word-original hebrew">אֱ֝לֹהַ֗/י</span>
  <span class="word-translit">&#x27;eloHa/i</span>
  <span class="word-english">God/ my</span>
  <span class="word-strongs"><a href="../lexicon/h430.html">H430</a></span>
</span><span class="interlinear-word" data-strongs="H9005">
  <span class="word-original hebrew">לְ/עוֹלָ֥ם</span>
  <span class="word-translit">le/&#x27;oLam</span>
  <span class="word-english">for/ ever</span>
  <span class="word-strongs">H9005</span>
</span><span class="interlinear-word" data-strongs="H3034">
  <span class="word-original hebrew">אוֹדֶֽ/ךָּ\׃</span>
  <span class="word-translit">&#x27;oDe/ka</span>
  <span class="word-english">I will give thanks to/ you</span>
  <span class="word-strongs"><a href="../lexicon/h3034.html">H3034</a></span>
</span></div>
    <div class="tn-note">
      <strong>&#x1f4dd; Cultural Note:</strong> Here, **so that** marks **my glory may sing praise to you and not be silent** as the goal or purpose of “You have turned for me, my mourning into dancing; you have loosed my sackcloth and have clothed me with gladness” in the previous verse. Use a connector in your language that makes it clear that this is the purpose. Alternate translation: [for the purpose that] or [to the end that]
    </div>
    <div class="tn-note">
      <strong>&#x1f4dd; Cultural Note:</strong> By **my glory**, David probably means some part of his inner being that represented where his honor was. You could indicate this explicitly in your translation if that would be helpful to your readers. Alternate translation: [my soul may sing praise to you] or [I may sing praise to you]
    </div>
    <div class="tn-note">
      <strong>&#x1f4dd; Cultural Note:</strong> David is not using this possessive form **my God** to indicate that he possesses or controls Yahweh. Rather, David is using these words to indicate that Yahweh is the God whom he worships. Alternate translation: [Yahweh, the God I worship]
    </div>
      </section>
      
